      "inline_content": "TinyContacts is a streamlined, modern contact management application designed to provide individuals and small teams with an elegant, distraction-free solution for organizing their professional and personal networks. In an era where contact information is scattered across multiple platforms, email clients, social media networks, and handwritten notes, TinyContacts offers a unified, centralized repository that puts you back in control of your connections. The application embodies the philosophy of \"simplicity without sacrifice\" - delivering essential contact management features without the bloat and complexity that plague enterprise CRM systems. TinyContacts is intentionally designed as a lightweight, focused tool that does one thing exceptionally well: helping you maintain and organize contact information efficiently. The application features an intuitive single-page interface with modal-based editing, ensuring users can add, update, search, and manage contacts with minimal cognitive load and maximum efficiency. TinyContacts is built on modern web technologies that ensure fast performance, responsive design across devices, and a user experience that feels native and fluid. Whether accessing the application from a desktop workstation, tablet, or mobile device, users experience the same consistent, polished interface optimized for their screen size and interaction patterns. It eschews unnecessary features like complex workflow automation, AI-powered relationship scoring, or elaborate social media integrations in favor of rock-solid reliability, blazing-fast performance, and an interface so intuitive that users require zero training. The application is designed to be immediately useful from the moment of first launch, with sensible defaults and an empty-state experience that guides users toward their first successful contact creation. Built with modern Python FastAPI backend and React TypeScript frontend, the codebase is clean, well-documented, and structured for easy extension. This makes TinyContacts an ideal candidate for demonstrating the capabilities of the GiljoAI MCP orchestration system, where specialized agents can collaborate on distinct features, modules, and layers of the application architecture. While enterprise solutions like Salesforce, HubSpot, and Microsoft Dynamics dominate the high-end CRM market, and basic address books ship with operating systems and email clients, there exists a significant gap for individuals and small teams who need more than a simple address book but less than a full CRM platform. TinyContacts fills this gap perfectly, offering professional-grade contact management without enterprise complexity or pricing. The target user persona for TinyContacts includes freelancers, consultants, small business owners, researchers, writers, event organizers, and anyone who maintains a professional network but doesn't require (or want) the overhead of enterprise software. These users value their time, appreciate clean design, and want tools that enhance their productivity rather than demanding extensive configuration and learning curves. The application stores all contact data locally by default, ensuring users maintain complete ownership and control of their information. This privacy-first approach resonates with users increasingly concerned about data sovereignty and the commercialization of personal information. Version 2.0 will introduce optional authentication and multi-user support, enabling small teams to share contact databases. Version 3.0 plans to add import/export capabilities for vCard and CSV formats, enabling migration from other contact management tools. Future versions may explore optional cloud synchronization, mobile native applications, and browser extensions for capturing contact information from web pages and email signatures. Accessibility is a core design principle, with TinyContacts adhering to WCAG 2.1 Level AA standards. The interface is fully keyboard-navigable, screen reader compatible, and designed with sufficient color contrast and scalable typography. Form validation provides clear, actionable error messages, and all interactive elements feature appropriate ARIA labels and roles. The backend API maintains >85% code coverage with pytest, while frontend components are validated with React Testing Library and Cypress for E2E workflows. This robust testing foundation ensures confidence during refactoring and feature additions, supporting the rapid iteration cycles that characterize modern software development. This comprehensive documentation serves both end users seeking to maximize their productivity and developers looking to understand, extend, or integrate with the application. The application's modest resource requirements mean it runs comfortably on minimal infrastructure, reducing hosting costs and environmental impact. The TinyContacts user interface leverages modern design patterns including card- based layouts, modal dialogs, contextual menus, and responsive grid systems. Visual feedback accompanies all user actions through subtle animations, loading states, and success confirmations. The application implements fuzzy search algorithms that tolerate typos and partial matches, enabling users to quickly locate contacts even with imperfect recall. Email addresses are validated against RFC standards but accept international characters and new TLDs. This validation approach prevents obvious errors while accommodating the diversity of real-world contact information. Photo management in TinyContacts includes automatic image optimization, generating appropriately sized thumbnails and display versions from uploaded originals. The system accepts common image formats (JPEG, PNG, GIF, WebP) and applies sensible file size limits to prevent storage bloat. Users can easily update or remove contact photos, with the interface providing instant visual feedback during upload operations. Beyond typical birthdays and anniversaries, users can define custom date types such as \"First Meeting,\" \"Contract Renewal,\" \"Project Deadline,\" or any other milestone worth remembering. TinyContacts employs progressive enhancement principles, ensuring core functionality works even in degraded network conditions or older browsers. JavaScript enhancements provide the optimal experience, but the application remains usable with basic HTML form submissions as a fallback. When errors occur, users receive plain-language explanations of what went wrong and actionable steps to resolve the issue. Technical error details are logged for developer diagnosis but hidden from end users unless debugging mode is enabled. Network failures trigger automatic retry logic with exponential backoff, preventing transient connectivity issues from disrupting workflows. Internationalization support is planned for future TinyContacts releases, with the architecture designed to accommodate multiple languages and locales. String literals are externalized into resource files, date and number formatting respects user locale preferences, and the UI layout accommodates languages with different text directionality (RTL support). Users must explicitly enable usage analytics, and can review exactly what data is collected before granting permission. The analytics system operates independently from core functionality, ensuring privacy-conscious users receive full product value without data sharing. The application exposes well-documented APIs that enable third-party integrations, extensions, and complementary tools. A planned plugin architecture will allow developers to extend functionality without modifying core code, fostering a community of contributors who can customize the application to specialized needs. The codebase follows consistent style guides enforced by automated linting, includes comprehensive inline documentation, and undergoes regular refactoring to prevent architectural erosion. Dependency management is active, with regular updates to address security vulnerabilities and leverage improvements in underlying libraries and frameworks. While competitors offer more features, they often overwhelm users with complexity and raise privacy concerns through aggressive data collection. TinyContacts competes on doing the essentials exceptionally well, loading instantly, respecting user privacy, and never getting in the way of actual work. {Description (Context for Orchestrator)} Modern contact management application for individuals and small teams. Streamlined CRUD interface for managing contacts with photos, emails, phone numbers, and important dates. Single-page React app with FastAPI backend, featuring instant search, modal-based editing, and local-first architecture. Key features: photo uploads with automatic optimization, important dates tracking (birthdays, anniversaries), tag-based organization, fuzzy search, export capabilities. Backend organized into distinct service modules (ProductService, ProjectService, OrchestrationService) with clear boundaries and responsibilities. MVC-inspired separation with FastAPI routers (controllers), service layer (business logic), and SQLAlchemy models (data). {API Style and Communication} REST API (primary interface, JSON payloads) OpenAPI 3.0 (automatic documentation via FastAPI) WebSocket (real-time updates for multi-user scenarios, planned v2.0) Multipart/form-data (photo uploads) Server-Sent Events (optional for live updates) HTTP/2 support (via modern ASGI servers) CORS configuration (cross-origin support for SPA) Security: input validation via Pydantic, parameterized queries prevent SQL injection, CSRF protection for multi-user deployments. Photo uploads with automatic resizing and optimization (thumbnail, card, full-size variants). Accessibility: WCAG 2.1 Level AA compliance, keyboard navigation, screen reader support. The selection of Python 3.11+ as the primary backend language reflects several strategic considerations. Python's ecosystem provides mature, battle-tested libraries for web development, database interaction, and image processing. Python 3.11 introduces significant performance improvements over earlier versions, with benchmarks showing 10-60% faster execution for typical web application workloads. Type hints and modern Python features like match statements, exception groups, and enhanced error messages contribute to more robust, self-documenting code. The Python runtime's cross-platform compatibility ensures TinyContacts deploys consistently across Windows, macOS, and Linux environments without platform- specific code branches. Package management via pip and virtual environments provides isolated, reproducible dependency installation that prevents version conflicts and simplifies deployment. From a developer productivity standpoint, Python's extensive standard library reduces the need for third-party dependencies for common tasks like datetime manipulation, file I/O, regular expressions, and JSON processing. This minimizes the application's dependency footprint and reduces supply chain security risks. The Python community's strong emphasis on testing, documentation, and code quality aligns perfectly with TinyContacts' engineering values. Tools like pytest, black, ruff, and mypy integrate seamlessly into development workflows, enforcing consistency and catching bugs before they reach production. FastAPI serves as the backbone of TinyContacts' REST API layer, chosen for its modern design, exceptional performance, and developer-friendly features. Built on Starlette and Pydantic, FastAPI delivers async request handling that outperforms traditional synchronous Python web frameworks by significant margins in benchmarks. The framework's dependency injection system enables clean separation of concerns, making route handlers focused and testable. Type hints drive automatic request validation and response serialization, eliminating boilerplate code while providing excellent IDE autocomplete support. FastAPI's async capabilities enable efficient handling of I/O-bound operations like database queries and file uploads without blocking the event loop. This concurrency model allows TinyContacts to serve multiple requests simultaneously on modest hardware, improving responsiveness under load. The framework's middleware system provides elegant solutions for cross-cutting concerns like CORS, request logging, error handling, and performance monitoring. Built-in support for modern authentication patterns (OAuth2, JWT) positions the application for future multi-user features. FastAPI's active development community, comprehensive documentation, and growing adoption in production environments provide confidence in the framework's longevity and support. Regular updates deliver performance improvements, security patches, and new features without breaking existing code. SQLite serves as the default database for single-user installations, offering zero-configuration setup, serverless architecture, and file-based storage that simplifies backups and migrations. SQLite's reliability (tested to 100% branch coverage) and broad platform support make it ideal for desktop and personal use cases. The database handles thousands of contacts with sub- millisecond query times, especially when proper indexes cover search and filter operations. For team deployments and scenarios requiring concurrent multi-user access, PostgreSQL provides enterprise-grade reliability, ACID compliance, and advanced features like JSON columns for flexible schema evolution. The application's data access layer abstracts database-specific details through SQLAlchemy ORM, enabling seamless switching between SQLite and PostgreSQL via configuration changes. Database migrations are managed through Alembic, providing version-controlled schema evolution and safe production upgrades. Both databases support the application's data model efficiently, with foreign key constraints ensuring referential integrity, indexes optimizing common query patterns, and transactions maintaining consistency during concurrent operations. SQLAlchemy 2.0 represents a major evolution in Python's premier database toolkit, introducing modern async support, improved type hinting, and more intuitive APIs. The framework's powerful ORM abstracts database specifics while providing escape hatches for raw SQL when needed. SQLModel bridges SQLAlchemy and Pydantic, enabling database models that double as API schemas. This reduces code duplication and ensures consistency between database layer and API contracts. Models define validation rules once, applied both during database writes and API request handling. The ORM's relationship loading strategies (lazy, eager, subquery) enable optimization of N+1 query problems common in contact management scenarios. Selective eager loading fetches contact photos and important dates efficiently, minimizing database round-trips. Database schema evolution becomes a controlled, reviewable process rather than risky manual alterations. The framework's extensive configuration options tune behavior for specific deployment contexts. React provides the foundation for TinyContacts' user interface, chosen for its component-based architecture, virtual DOM performance, and massive ecosystem. The library's maturity and widespread adoption ensure long-term support, abundant learning resources, and a steady stream of community contributions. Transitions API provides fine-grained control over loading states and progressive enhancement of content. TypeScript integration adds static type checking to JavaScript, catching errors during development rather than runtime. Type definitions for props, state, and function signatures serve as living documentation and enable intelligent IDE autocomplete. The compiler's strictness prevents common bugs like null reference errors, undefined property access, and type mismatches. Custom hooks encapsulate reusable logic for API calls, form handling, and local storage synchronization, promoting DRY principles and testability. These libraries integrate seamlessly, providing battle-tested patterns for common SPA challenges. React's component model encourages UI decomposition into small, focused, reusable pieces. ContactCard, ContactForm, DatesEditor, and SearchBar components each handle specific responsibilities, tested in isolation and composed into complete features. Vite revolutionizes the frontend development experience with near-instantaneous server startup and lightning-fast hot module replacement. Vite's plugin ecosystem provides seamless integration with TypeScript, React, CSS preprocessors, and various asset types. Configuration remains minimal for standard setups while exposing extensive customization for advanced needs. API requests route through Vite's dev server to the backend, simplifying the development environment setup. This rapid feedback cycle supports iterative development and makes comprehensive rebuilds practical within continuous integration pipelines. Tailwind CSS provides utility-first styling that accelerates UI development without sacrificing customization. The framework's comprehensive utility classes cover spacing, typography, colors, layout, and responsive design, enabling developers to style components without leaving HTML/JSX. The JIT (Just-In-Time) compiler generates only the CSS classes actually used in the application, producing minimal stylesheets regardless of Tailwind's full feature set. This eliminates concerns about framework bloat and delivers tiny CSS bundles that load instantly. Customization happens through configuration, defining color palettes, spacing scales, and design tokens that propagate throughout the application. The utility-first approach eliminates decision paralysis around class naming conventions and CSS architecture patterns. Developers focus on implementing designs rather than debating BEM, OOCSS, or SMACSS methodologies. TanStack Query revolutionizes data fetching in React applications through powerful caching, background refetching, and optimistic updates. Stale data refetches when users focus the application or reconnect after network interruptions, ensuring they always see current information. When a contact is updated, related queries invalidate automatically, triggering refetches that propagate changes throughout the UI. Optimistic updates enhance perceived performance by immediately reflecting changes in the UI before server confirmation. The library manages rollback if API calls fail, preserving consistency without sacrificing responsiveness. The library's DevTools provide visibility into query states, cache contents, and fetch timings during development. This observability accelerates debugging and optimization, revealing inefficient fetch patterns and caching opportunities. Built-in support for pagination, infinite scrolling, and parallel queries handles common data fetching patterns with minimal code. Mutations abstract API calls that modify data, integrating with query invalidation to maintain cache consistency. The library leverages uncontrolled components and refs to minimize React's re-rendering overhead, making complex forms with many fields responsive and smooth. Email, phone, and required field validations are defined once and applied consistently across create and edit forms. The library's register function connects form inputs with minimal boilerplate, eliminating the controlled component ceremony of value/onChange props. Validation triggers on blur, change, or submit events based on configuration, balancing immediate feedback with avoiding premature error messages. Form state management through useForm hook provides access to dirty fields, touched inputs, validation errors, and submission status. Field array support handles the dynamic important dates list elegantly. Users add, remove, and reorder date entries with the library managing array state and validation. Pillow handles server-side image processing for contact photos, providing resize, crop, and format conversion capabilities. Uploaded images are automatically resized to appropriate dimensions for display, reducing storage requirements and accelerating page loads. The srcset attribute in image tags enables browsers to select appropriate variants based on display density and viewport size. JPEG for photos and PNG for graphics with transparency ensures efficient file sizes without quality degradation. Modern format support (WebP, AVIF) provides additional optimization for capable browsers through progressive enhancement. The library's robust error handling gracefully rejects invalid uploads with clear user feedback. Lanczos resampling produces sharp thumbnails from larger images without artifacts, maintaining professional appearance at all sizes. This structure prevents single directories from containing excessive files, which can degrade filesystem performance. File naming strategies use unique identifiers to prevent collisions and enable safe concurrent uploads. UUIDs or sequential IDs combined with original extensions create filenames that are URL-safe, unique, and recognizable. The uploads directory copies independently of database backups, or together in complete system snapshots. File cleanup processes remove orphaned images when contacts are deleted, preventing storage bloat. Background tasks or deletion hooks ensure the filesystem and database remain synchronized, avoiding dead references. Uvicorn serves as the ASGI server running the FastAPI application, chosen for its performance, standards compliance, and production readiness. The server's async architecture handles concurrent requests efficiently, critical for responsive APIs. Hot reload during development accelerates iteration cycles, automatically restarting the server when code changes. This eliminates manual server restarts and maintains rapid feedback loops during feature development. Gunicorn or similar process managers can spawn multiple Uvicorn workers, distributing load across available hardware for improved throughput. HTTPX provides a test client that makes requests to the FastAPI application without network calls. This enables fast, reliable API integration tests that verify endpoint behavior, validation rules, and error handling in isolation. Component tests verify rendering, user interactions, and state changes in isolation from the backend. Cypress end-to-end tests validate complete user workflows, from opening the application through creating, editing, searching, and deleting contacts. Coverage reports integrate into CI pipelines, failing builds that drop below configured thresholds. The same mock definitions serve development and testing, ensuring consistency and reducing setup overhead. Ruff provides extremely fast Python linting, checking code against extensive rule sets in milliseconds. The tool catches common errors, style violations, and potential bugs before they reach runtime or code review. Consistent formatting across the codebase reduces cognitive load and makes diffs more meaningful during code review. Pre-commit hooks run linters and formatters automatically before commits, preventing style violations from entering version control. Git provides distributed version control with powerful branching, merging, and history management. Conventional commit messages create a readable project history that supports automated changelog generation. Commit types (feat, fix, docs, refactor) categorize changes and enable semantic versioning automation. The repository structure separates backend and frontend code into distinct directories with independent dependency management. Requirements files pin dependency versions exactly, ensuring consistent environments across development, testing, and production. Virtual environments isolate Python dependencies per project, preventing version conflicts between applications. NPM manages JavaScript dependencies with lock files that guarantee reproducible installs. Package scripts define common tasks (dev, build, test) with standardized commands across projects. Security scanning via tools like Safety (Python) and npm audit detects vulnerable dependencies. Docker containerization packages the complete application with dependencies, ensuring consistent behavior across environments. Docker Compose orchestrates multi-container setups, running backend, frontend, and database services together. Traditional deployment via virtual environments and process managers (Gunicorn, PM2) provides straightforward hosting on VPS or dedicated servers. The logging strategy captures application events at appropriate levels (DEBUG, INFO, WARNING, ERROR, CRITICAL), enabling filtering and routing based on severity. Request/response logging tracks API usage patterns, performance metrics, and error rates. API documentation generates automatically from FastAPI route decorators and Pydantic models. The interactive Swagger UI enables testing endpoints without building API clients, accelerating development and debugging. Markdown documents capture architecture decisions, setup instructions, and development guides. The format's simplicity and GitHub rendering make documentation accessible without special tools. IDE integration surfaces documentation during development, reducing context switching to external references. These benefits span efficiency gains, cognitive relief, professional empowerment, and personal satisfaction. Let's explore each dimension in depth, examining how the application transforms the contact management experience from a tedious chore into an effortless, even enjoyable, aspect of professional and personal life. The most immediate and measurable benefit of TinyContacts is the dramatic reduction in time spent managing contact information. The application's instant search functionality returns results as users type, typically surfacing the desired contact within 2-3 keystrokes. This search speed, combined with the visual presentation of results showing names, photos, and key details, enables contact retrieval in seconds rather than minutes. This friction reduction makes users more likely to maintain accurate, current contact information rather than tolerating outdated data because updating it is tedious. The batch operation capabilities planned for future versions will amplify efficiency gains. TinyContacts enables these workflows with bulk operations that would require hours of manual data entry in traditional systems. No separate image editing tools, no manual resizing, no concerns about file formats or sizes - the application handles these details transparently. The important dates feature prevents missed birthdays, anniversaries, and other significant occasions. Data export capabilities (planned feature) enable easy migration to other systems if needs change. The application's responsive design ensures users access their contacts from any device without installing separate mobile apps or dealing with synchronization issues. The same familiar interface works on desktop, tablet, and phone, eliminating the learning curve of platform-specific applications. These shortcuts enable contact management without touching the mouse, appealing to keyboard-centric users who value efficiency. Auto-save functionality ensures users never lose work due to forgotten save buttons or browser crashes. As users type in contact fields, changes save automatically after brief pauses, providing peace of mind and eliminating the anxiety of potential data loss. Beyond quantifiable time savings, TinyContacts delivers significant cognitive benefits by reducing mental load and decision fatigue. TinyContacts serves as a reliable external memory system, offloading this burden and freeing mental resources for more valuable activities. TinyContacts' contact cards display photos prominently, leveraging humans' exceptional face recognition abilities. Users recognize contacts visually before consciously remembering names, making